│ call i32 (ptr, ...) @printf(ptr null, i32 %add1)\"\nfollowed immediately │
│ by the assertion. In the code, control dependencies are processed via    │
│ DecrUnsched(Dep, /*IsControl=*/true). The lambda DecrUnsched contains a  │
│ condition that allows decrementing even if hasValidDependencies() is     │
│ false when IsControl is true:\n\n  if ((IsControl ||                     │
│ Data->hasValidDependencies()) &&\n                                       │
│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) { ... }\n\nThis directly        │
│ contradicts incrementUnscheduledDeps' assertion requiring valid          │
│ dependencies.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n-                              │
│ ScheduleData::incrementUnscheduledDeps asserts                           │
│ hasValidDependencies().\n- DecrUnsched allows calling                    │
│ incrementUnscheduledDeps when IsControl is true, regardless of           │
│ dependency validity, presumably to handle certain control dep            │
│ scenarios.\n- This mismatch causes the assertion to fire when a control  │
│ dependency has not yet had its dependency count initialized.\n- The      │
│ design intent elsewhere: ScheduleData::clearDirectDependencies retains   │
│ memory/control deps but sets Dependencies to InvalidDeps and resets      │
│ UnscheduledDeps, meaning control/memory deps should only be decremented  │
│ after their dependency counts are initialized. The permissive            │
│ DecrUnsched path violates this.\n\nTherefore, the bug is that            │
│ DecrUnsched should not call incrementUnscheduledDeps unless              │
│ hasValidDependencies() is true, even for control dependencies.\n\n4.     │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:                                          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Location: In          │
│ BlockScheduling::schedule(), within the lambda DecrUnsched defined       │
│ around lines 5401-5434.\n- Change the condition from `(IsControl ||      │
│ Data->hasValidDependencies())` to `Data->hasValidDependencies()` so that │
│ we never call incrementUnscheduledDeps unless the dependency info is     │
│ valid. This aligns with the assertion and avoids                         │
│ crashing.\n\nEdit:\nReplace:\n  if ((IsControl ||                        │
│ Data->hasValidDependencies()) &&\n                                       │
│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) {\nwith:\n  if                  │
│ (Data->hasValidDependencies() &&\n                                       │
│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) {\n\nThis ensures control       │
│ dependencies are only decremented when their dependency counters have    │
│ been computed, consistent with the invariant enforced by                 │
│ incrementUnscheduledDeps.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from a      │
│ logical inconsistency: allowing decrement of unscheduled dependencies    │
│ for control deps without ensuring dependency info is valid. Tightening   │
│ DecrUnsched to require hasValidDependencies for all cases prevents       │
│ calling incrementUnscheduledDeps on invalid data, satisfying the         │
│ assertion and preserving scheduler invariants. This fix avoids the abort │
│ without altering scheduling semantics, since readiness must be based on  │
│ correctly initialized dependency counts."})                              │
